{
  "issues": {
    "001": {
      "verdict": "real",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/filters.py:5 — `from collections import Iterable` is present. This import was removed in Python 3.10+; confirmed by running `from collections import Iterable` on Python 3.11 which raises ImportError."
    },
    "002": {
      "verdict": "real",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/filters.py:59 — `return bool(eval(expr, {\"__builtins__\": {}}, {\"entry\": entry}))` uses eval() on user-supplied expressions. Even with empty builtins, the LogEntry object's attributes are accessible, enabling arbitrary attribute access and potential code execution."
    },
    "003": {
      "verdict": "fabricated",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/parser.py contains no SQL query construction whatsoever. The file only defines a regex-based log line parser (LOG_LINE_RE at line 13) and a LogEntry dataclass. There is no database export pipeline or SQL anywhere in the codebase."
    },
    "004": {
      "verdict": "real",
      "evidence": "README.md:10 — The Features section lists 'Real-time tail mode for live log streams'. However, cli.py has no --tail argument (see build_parser() at lines 22-35), and no streaming/tail logic exists anywhere in the codebase."
    },
    "005": {
      "verdict": "fabricated",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/cli.py:33 — `--top` is defined with `type=int, default=None`, which argparse handles correctly. It is used at line 64 as `by_url(entries, top=args.top)`. No AttributeError occurs; the flag works as intended."
    },
    "006": {
      "verdict": "real",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/experimental.py exists with functions detect_anomalies() and session_window(), but a grep across the entire codebase shows zero imports of experimental from any other module. The module is dead code."
    },
    "007": {
      "verdict": "fabricated",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/web.py does not exist. There is no web interface in the codebase at all — the tool is purely CLI-based. The file cited in the issue is entirely fabricated."
    },
    "008": {
      "verdict": "fabricated",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/parser.py:60-87 — parse_line() does line.strip() and regex matching. There is no truncation to 8192 characters or any byte limit. The function processes the full line regardless of length."
    },
    "009": {
      "verdict": "fabricated",
      "evidence": "The issue claims format_legacy() is in output.py, but it is actually in logalyzer/utils.py:21. output.py contains only to_json, to_csv, to_text, and render_aggregate. Per the rules, a wrong file citation makes the issue fabricated."
    },
    "010": {
      "verdict": "fabricated",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/io.py:36-42 — load_iter() opens its own file handle per call and iterates line-by-line. Each concurrent call gets an independent file descriptor; there is no shared mutable state between calls. The claimed race condition between 'file-handle creation and iteration' does not exist."
    },
    "011": {
      "verdict": "fabricated",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/aggregate.py:11-16 — by_status() simply iterates entries and increments Counter[e.status] for each. There is no special handling for 3xx codes and no deduplication logic. Each entry is counted exactly once regardless of status code. The claim of double-counting is incorrect."
    },
    "012": {
      "verdict": "fabricated",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/cache.py does not exist. There is no caching layer anywhere in the codebase. The file cited in the issue is entirely fabricated."
    },
    "013": {
      "verdict": "real",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/io.py:24 — `result = result + [entry]` creates a new list each iteration (O(n²) for n entries). logalyzer/io.py:27 — `accumulated = accumulated + ch` concatenates character-by-character (O(n²) for n characters). Both are genuine performance anti-patterns."
    },
    "014": {
      "verdict": "real",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/filters.py:36 — `return entry.ip in allowlist` uses list membership testing. In cli.py:47, allowlist is args.ip which is a list (from action='append'). For large allowlists, this is O(n) per lookup instead of O(1) with a set."
    },
    "015": {
      "verdict": "fabricated",
      "evidence": "logalyzer/__init__.py contains only `__version__ = \"0.2.0\"` (line 3). It does not import LogEntry from parser or anything else. The claim that it imports LogEntry is false."
    }
  },
  "summary": {
    "real_count": 6,
    "fabricated_count": 9
  }
}
